Yes — in the method lookup chain you almost always see:

Object
Kernel
BasicObject

Why are these always there?

Let’s break it from absolute zero.

🧱 1️⃣ Everything in Ruby is an Object

In Ruby:

5.class        # => Integer
"hi".class     # => String
[].class       # => Array

All of these classes ultimately inherit from Object.

So the inheritance hierarchy looks like this:

BasicObject
   ↑
 Object
   ↑
 YourClass

That’s why Object and BasicObject always appear.

🧠 2️⃣ What is BasicObject?

BasicObject is the most minimal class in Ruby.

It has almost nothing.

It exists so Ruby has a root parent.

Example:

BasicObject.instance_methods

Very few methods.

Why does it exist?

👉 To provide the absolute minimum behavior.
👉 Used when building proxy objects.
👉 Used when you want a "blank slate" object.

🧠 3️⃣ What is Object?

Object is the default parent of all classes.

When you write:

class Dog
end

It is actually:

class Dog < Object
end

So every normal class inherits from Object.

Object gives you methods like:

puts

class

is_a?

nil?

to_s

That’s why you can call those methods everywhere.

🧠 4️⃣ What is Kernel?

Kernel is a module.

It is included into Object.

Meaning:

Object.include Kernel

So every class inherits methods from Kernel.

Kernel gives methods like:

puts

print

raise

loop

sleep

require

Example:

puts "hello"

Why can you call puts without a receiver?

Because:

puts is defined in Kernel

Kernel is included in Object

Your class inherits from Object

So you automatically get Kernel methods.

🔍 Why They Always Appear in Lookup Chain

Let’s inspect:

class Dog
end

Dog.ancestors

You’ll see something like:

[Dog, Object, Kernel, BasicObject]

Why?

Because:

Dog inherits Object
Object includes Kernel
Object inherits BasicObject

So Ruby searches in that order.

🔥 Simple Visual Hierarchy
BasicObject
   ↑
 Object  ← includes Kernel
   ↑
 Dog

When you call:

dog.some_method

Ruby searches:

Dog

Object

Kernel

BasicObject

method_missing

That’s the lookup chain.

🎯 Why Ruby Designed It This Way

Ruby wanted:

A minimal root (BasicObject)

A default useful parent (Object)

A place for global utility methods (Kernel)

Clean separation of responsibilities.

🧠 Interview-Level Explanation

If interviewer asks:

“Why do Object, Kernel, and BasicObject always appear in method lookup chain?”

Strong answer:

All classes in Ruby inherit from Object by default, and Object inherits from BasicObject. Additionally, the Kernel module is included into Object, which makes its methods available globally. That’s why they always appear in the method lookup chain.

That answer shows deep understanding.